                    <font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="3"><br>
                      <b>L&#8217;agriculture biologique encaisse un mauvais
                        cout<br>
                      </b>Afin de faire des &laquo; &eacute;conomies &raquo;, le
                      gouvernement fait fl&egrave;che de tout bois, s&#8217;attaquant
                      aujourd&#8217;hui au cr&eacute;dit d&#8217;imp&ocirc;t pour l&#8217;agriculture
                      biologique en le divisant par deux.<br>
                      Le projet de loi de finances 2011, qui vient
                      d&#8217;&ecirc;tre adopt&eacute; par le S&eacute;nat, r&eacute;duit de 4 000 &agrave; 2
                      000 &#8364; le montant du cr&eacute;dit d&#8217;imp&ocirc;t sur le revenu
                      dont b&eacute;n&eacute;ficient les agriculteurs convertis &agrave;
                      l&#8217;agriculture biologique. Une mesure drastique &agrave;
                      l&#8217;&eacute;chelle des fermes, sous couvert d&#8217;&eacute;conomie
                      d&#8217;argent public, mais une &eacute;conomie globale somme
                      toute bien d&eacute;risoire compar&eacute;e aux autres p&ocirc;les de
                      financement pr&eacute;vu par le projet de loi.<br>
                      Ce cr&eacute;dit d&#8217;imp&ocirc;t avait comme principal m&eacute;rite de
                      remettre un peu de justice dans l&#8217;attribution des
                      aides, notamment parce qu&#8217;il ciblait surtout les
                      petites structures qui n&#8217;en percevaient pas ou
                      tr&egrave;s peu. L&#8217;annonce du doublement de celui-ci
                      avait &eacute;t&eacute; faite en fanfare &agrave; la suite du Grenelle
                      de l&#8217;environnement. Elle n&#8217;aura pas &eacute;t&eacute; effective
                      bien longtemps&#8230;<br>
                      L&#8217;agriculture biologique est aujourd&#8217;hui la plus &agrave;
                      m&ecirc;me de pr&eacute;server concr&egrave;tement et durablement les
                      ressources naturelles, la biodiversit&eacute; et la
                      richesse des sols. Cette mesure financi&egrave;re est un
                      message tr&egrave;s n&eacute;gatif adress&eacute; &agrave; la Bio et une
                      trahison compl&egrave;te des objectifs affich&eacute;s par le
                      Grenelle de l&#8217;environnement. Cela n&#8217;emp&ecirc;che pas la
                      France de clamer son soutien au d&eacute;veloppement du
                      mode de production biologique afin de r&eacute;duire
                      l&#8217;usage des pesticides. Lanc&eacute; en 2007, le plan &laquo;
                      Agriculture biologique : horizon 2012 &raquo; visait &agrave;
                      tripler les surfaces cultiv&eacute;es en bio pour les
                      porter &agrave; 6 % de la surface agricole fran&ccedil;aise en
                      2012. On est encore bien loin de cet objectif
                      puisque les surfaces cultiv&eacute;es en bio s'&eacute;levaient
                      fin 2009 &agrave; 670 000 hectares&#8230; soit seulement 2,6 %
                      de la surface agricole utilis&eacute;e. Cette coupe
                      franche dans les cr&eacute;dits ne va s&ucirc;rement pas aider
                      !<br>
                      Alors que la demande fran&ccedil;aise de produits bio va
                      croissant, que les taux de surface en conversion
                      n&#8217;y suffisent pas et que la relocalisation fait
                      des &eacute;mules, que restera t-il au march&eacute; Bio
                      fran&ccedil;ais pour s&#8217;approvisionner ? L&#8217;importation ?
                      Est-ce vraiment une solution souhaitable et
                      p&eacute;renne ? En aucun cas !<br>
                      Ne serait-il pas plus coh&eacute;rent d&#8217;encourager la
                      production biologique locale ?<br>
                      Nature &amp; Progr&egrave;s, la Conf&eacute;d&eacute;ration Paysanne et
                      la F&eacute;d&eacute;ration Nationale d&#8217;Agriculture Biologique
                      (FNAB) demandent vivement &agrave; ce que le Minist&egrave;re de
                      l&#8217;&eacute;conomie revoie sa copie, en accord avec les
                      annonces du Grenelle.<br>
                      Voir : <a
href="http://www.gabnor.org/index.php/actualites/l-agriculture-biologique-encaisse-un-mauvais-cout.html">http://www.gabnor.org/index.php/actualites/<br>
l-agriculture-biologique-encaisse-un-mauvais-cout.html</a><br>
                      <br>
                      <br>
                      <b>Pork is on the Menu at Alltech&#8217;s International
                        Forum on Pork Production (<i>Second annual
                          meeting, a tribute to Dr. Des Cole)<br>
                        </i></b>[Dunboyne, IRELAND] &#8211; Global leaders in
                      the swine industry gathered in Lexington, Kentucky
                      on December 1st and 2nd, for Alltech&#8217;s <a
                        href="http://www.alltech.com/blog">International
                        Forum on Pork Production: A tribute to Dr. Des
                        Cole</a>. The forum comprised two days of
                      discussion on the key issues facing the global pig
                      industry. Topics included: the removal of
                      antibiotic growth promoters, risk management, sow
                      productivity, and how to tackle multi-factorial
                      diseases.<br>
                      <br>
                      Discussions began with Joe Kerns, a 25-year
                      veteran of risk management consulting with the
                      International Agribusiness Group. He emphasised
                      that we can&#8217;t try to outguess the market but need
                      to manage what is controllable &#8211; i.e. input costs,
                      which dramatically increased in 2010. Kerns
                      expects prices to continue to climb in 2011 giving
                      further impetus to the need for strong risk
                      management programmes.<br>
                      <br>
                      &gt;&gt; Dr. Gunner Sorensen with the <a
                        href="http://eng.vsp.lf.dk/">Pig Research Centre</a>
                      and <a
                        href="http://www.lf.dk/Helpers/In%20english.aspx">Danish
                        Agriculture and Food Council</a> addressed the
                      challenge of achieving more than 30 pigs per sow
                      per year. Key points included:<br>
                      - Maximum sow productivity must start with gilt
                      development.<br>
                      - Management of sow milk yield is critical if she
                      is to successfully nurse a large litter size. Feed
                      intake is integral in this respect.<br>
                      <br>
                      &gt;&gt; Tom Gillespie of <a
                        href="http://www.rssvet.com/index.php">Rensselaer
                        Swine Services</a> set forth a plan for
                      achieving optimum health and immunity. Since
                      co-infection is the most common complication in
                      the unit, Gillespie has chosen to focus on the
                      overall health of a unit instead of just one
                      disease. According to Gillespie, key elements of
                      this approach are developing an understanding of
                      both the flow of the target pathogen within the
                      herd and biosecurity issues.<br>
                      <br>
                      &gt;&gt; Dr. Bill Close of Close Consultancy spoke
                      on an era of no antimicrobial growth promoters
                      (AGPs). Close explained that the removal of AGPs
                      has led to an increase in AGPs for therapeutic
                      uses. However, this can be overcome with proper
                      management and nutrition. His suggestions
                      included: improving the intake and the quality of
                      the colostrums, correct diet specifications and
                      feed management, use of pro-active ingredients and
                      additives, development of a healthcare and
                      vaccination program, and the practice of good
                      management techniques and a proper environment.<br>
                      <br>
                      &gt;&gt; Bruce Mullan from the Department of
                      Agriculture, Western Australia wrapped up
                      Wednesday&#8217;s session at the International Forum on
                      Pork Production. He summarized some of the
                      questions and viewpoints that rose from the day&#8217;s
                      presentations and discussions and added some
                      observations of his own:<br>
                      <br>
                      &gt; With regard to Dr. Sorensen&#8217;s presentation on
                      sow productivity:<br>
                      - The important consideration is not just
                      productivity but productivity vs. cost per kilo of
                      pork produced.<br>
                      - It is fine to discuss the relationship between
                      milk production and feed intake but isn&#8217;t it
                      quality of the piglet at birth that starts it all?<br>
                      - Precision feeding &#8211; we have the technology but
                      are we ready to implement it?<br>
                      - Artificial rearing of piglets &#8211; it is possible
                      but is it economical?<br>
                      - We need to consider the possible effects on pork
                      quality<br>
                      <br>
                      &gt; With regard to Dr. Gillespie&#8217;s presentation
                      on swine health and immunity:<br>
                      - If you want good to great results you must
                      understand the behaviour of the pathogens involved
                      (shedding/persistence)<br>
                      - Application of available techniques requires
                      well trained and motivated people<br>
                      - Vaccines cannot prevent infections &#8211; know the
                      limitation of the tools that you use<br>
                      - Everything can fall apart with a break in
                      biosecurity (transport)<br>
                      Mullan concluded by saying that the pork
                      industry&#8217;s greatest challenge is to be accepted by
                      the public.<br>
                      <br>
                      &gt;&gt;&gt; About Alltech<br>
                      Alltech's third annual meeting in honour of Dr.
                      Des Cole will be held on the 14th to 16th
                      September 2011, in Lexington, Kentucky. Dr. Des
                      Cole pioneered modern pig science, advancing our
                      understanding of sow nutrition and protein and
                      amino acid metabolism. He developed the concept of
                      the &#8220;ideal protein&#8221; and laid the foundation for
                      feeding modern hyper prolific genotypes. During
                      his impressive career he published more than 300
                      papers and 25 books; taught at University of
                      Nottingham, and served as director of Nottingham
                      Nutrition International and managing editor of
                      Nottingham University Press. His many awards
                      include the 1985 David Black Award, and the 1990
                      Alltech Medal of Excellence. Dr. Cole passed away
                      in 2006. Alltech&#8217;s International Forum on Pork
                      Production was started in 2009 as a tribute to Des
                      Cole, his great contribution to pig science and
                      his legacy as a long time friend and business
                      associate. For further information, the entire
                      program can be followed on Alltech&#8217;s blog,<a
                        href="http://www.alltech.com/blog"> Innovations</a>.<br>
                      <a
                        href="http://www.alltech.com/en/Pages/default.aspx">Alltech</a>
                      is a global leader in natural animal nutrition,
                      headquartered in Lexington, Kentucky. With more
                      than 2300 employees in 120 countries, the company
                      has developed a strong regional presence in
                      Europe, North America, Latin America, the
                      Middle-East, Africa, and Asia-Pacific.<br>
                      See: <a href="http://www.alltech.com/">http://www.alltech.com/</a><br>
                      Twitter: <a
                        href="http://www.twitter.com/alltechtweets">www.twitter.com/alltechtweets</a><br>
                      Contact: Christina LOMBARD<br>
                      Email: clombard(a)alltech.com<br>
                      <br>
                      <br>
